STRINGS(1)                       User Commands                      STRINGS(1)

NAME
       strings - print the sequences of printable characters in files

SYNOPSIS
       strings [OPTION]... [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
       For each file given, print the sequences of printable characters
       that are at least 4 characters long (or the number given with the
       -n option).  By default, only the contents of initialized and
       loaded sections of object files are printed.

       If no file is specified, standard input is read.

OPTIONS
       -a, --all, -
              scan the whole file, not just the data section

       -d     scan only data sections of object files (default)

       -f, --print-file-name
              print the name of the file before each string

       -n, --bytes=MIN-LEN
              print sequences of at least MIN-LEN characters (default 4)

       -t, --radix=RADIX
              print the offset within the file before each string.
              RADIX is one of: o (octal), x (hex), d (decimal)

       -o     an alias for -t o (octal offset)

       -w, --include-all-whitespace
              include all whitespace as valid string characters

       -e, --encoding=ENCODING
              select the character encoding:
              s = single-7-bit-byte (ASCII, default)
              S = single-8-bit-byte (Latin)
              b = 16-bit bigendian
              l = 16-bit littleendian
              B = 32-bit bigendian
              L = 32-bit littleendian

       -T, --target=FORMAT
              specify the binary file format (accepted for compat)

       -s, --output-separator=SEP
              use SEP as the output record separator (default newline)

       -h, --help
              display this help and exit

       -V, -v, --version
              output version information and exit

EXIT STATUS
       0      if OK

       1      if errors occurred

AUTHORS
       LikeOS-64 project.

SEE ALSO
       hexdump(1), file(1), grep(1)

